[Event "Short & Sweet: The Vienna Game"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2...Bc5 3.f4 - Risky"]
[Black "...exf4 + ...Qh4+ - #1"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-vienna-game/course/28518, variation/4908711"]

1. e4 {We start with Fischer's favourite 1. e4! A move that allows White fast 
development and chances to fight for the centre.} e5 {[%cal Bb1c3] Usually, 1... 
e5 is the biggest nut to crack for the 1. e4 player. Most of the 1. e4 
aficionados are ready to face the Sicilian, the French and are happy with some 
sharp lines that may appear on the board. However, after 1... e5 things are far 
from clear. Times when White could destroy the opponent with romantic stuff such 
as the King's Gambit or the open Italian with d4 are gone due to the engines 
'arrival'. Fortunately, there is a solution! We can still get a nice attacking 
position if we enter the Vienna Opening!} 2. Nc3 ({This is the aforementioned 
Vienna opening. Normally, Black will be perfectly ready for such tries as the 
Spanish, Italian, Scotch etc. However, it is more likely that Black's players 
won't be as booked to the teeth with modern theory against the Vienna as against 
the more popular lines. Even if they know theory in main lines with} 2. Nc3 2... 
Nc6 3. f4) ({or} 2. Nc3 2... Nf6 3. f4 {, they probably won't expect us to 
change our plans and go for a modest 3. g3 instead after both 2... Nc6 or 2... 
Nf6! Only after 2... Bc5 we will play 3. f4.}) Bc5 {In the first place, we will 
take a look at this continuation. It is the 3rd most popular move for Black and 
you should expect to meet it approximately once every 15 games. Black wants to 
develop quickly, and it makes more sense to continue with ...d6 since the 
dark-squared Bishop is already on c5.} 3. f4 $5 {[%cal Bg1f3] This is the way to 
go for White. We are ready for a bare-knuckle fight. Other tries such as 3. Nf3 
or 3. Bc4 are less critical. Also, after 3. f4 White scores a very respectable 
60.8%.} exf4 {Black takes the pawn and threatens ...Qh4 at the same time.} 4. d4 
$1 {Remember, we are brave people! We shouldn't waste time with such moves as 
Nf3.} Qh4+ 5. Ke2 {[%cal Bg1f3][%csl Gd4,Ge4] White gets an improved version of 
the King's Gambit since we will win a tempo on the c5-Bishop.} Bb6 6. Nf3 {[%cal 
Bc1f4,Rh4h6,Gg2g3][%csl Rf4] White will take on f4 next with a big advantage in 
the centre.} Qe7 ({Trying to defend the pawn with} 6... Qh6 {is very risky due 
to} 7. g3 {. The Black Queen would be in danger on h6 while the f4-pawn will be 
lost sooner or later.}) 7. Bxf4 {[%cal Be2f2] The spirit of Steinitz is still 
alive.} d5 $6 {This was played in the only game that has reached this position. 
It is a thematic strike in the King's Gambit, but here, being a tempo up allows 
White to get a big advantage.} 8. Kf2 $1 {Just calmly stepping away from the 
e-file problems.} dxe4 9. Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Re7e4,Gf1b5,Gh1e1][%csl Re8,Re7] This 
is the whole point of White's operation. The Knight is taboo due to Bb5+ 
followed by Re1.} Qxe4 $2 {As I've mentioned, this loses.} 10. Bb5+ Kd8 11. Re1 
{[%cal Ge1e8][%csl Re4,Rd8]} Qxf4 12. Re8# {A nice way to win a game in 12 
moves!} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The Vienna Game"]
