1. e4 {We start with Fischer's favourite 1. e4! A move that allows White fast 
development and chances to fight for the centre.} e5 {Usually, 1... e5 is the 
biggest nut to crack for the 1. e4 player. Most of the 1. e4 aficionados are 
ready to face the Sicilian, the French and are happy with some sharp lines that 
may appear on the board. However, after 1... e5 things are far from clear. Times 
when White could destroy the opponent with romantic stuff such as the King's 
Gambit or the open Italian with d4 are gone due to the engines 'arrival'. 
Fortunately, there is a solution! We can still get a nice attacking position if 
we enter the Vienna Opening!} 2. Nc3 ({This is the aforementioned Vienna 
opening. Normally, Black will be perfectly ready for such tries as the Spanish, 
Italian, Scotch etc. However, it is more likely that Black's players won't be as 
booked to the teeth with modern theory against the Vienna as against the more 
popular lines. Even if they know theory in main lines with} 2. Nc3 2... Nc6 3. 
f4) ({or} 2. Nc3 2... Nf6 3. f4 {, they probably won't expect us to change our 
plans and go for a modest 3. g3 instead after both 2... Nc6 or 2... Nf6! Only 
after 2... Bc5 we will play 3. f4.}) Bc5 {In the first place, we will take a 
look at this continuation. It is the 3rd most popular move for Black and you 
should expect to meet it approximately once every 15 games. Black wants to 
develop quickly, and it makes more sense to continue with ...d6 since the 
dark-squared Bishop is already on c5.} 3. f4 $5 {This is the way to go for 
White. We are ready for a bare-knuckle fight. Other tries such as 3. Nf3 or 3. 
Bc4 are less critical. Also, after 3. f4 White scores a very respectable 60.8%.} 
d6 {This is the strongest move for Black. It allows our mighty opponent to keep 
the centre. The other tries should give White at least a slight edge.} 4. Nf3 
{Black's accurate 3... d6 forces us to enter the King's Gambit Declined 
positions. However, don't be too pessimistic about that! We've avoided a ton of 
2... exf4 lines and can confidently look to the future.} Nf6 (4... Nc6 5. Bc4 
Nf6 6. d3 {will lead to the same thing.}) 5. Bc4 Nc6 6. d3 {It looks like White 
may experience problems on the f2-square, but don't worry! If Black tries to put 
either of his minor pieces on g4 he will suffer.} a6 {[%cal Rc3a4,Gc5a7] The 
main idea of this move is to keep the Bishop with ...Ba7 if white plays ...Na4. 
Also, sometimes Black can push b5 and b4.} 7. f5 {[%csl Rc8,Gf5] White gains 
some space, blocks the c8-Bishop and prepares Bg5.} h6 ({Another alternative 
that is analyzed in the course is} 7... Na5 {.}) 8. Nd5 {White immediately tries 
to strip Black's kingside from defenders.} Na5 9. b4 $1 {Only this move 
guarantees White a good game.} Nxd5 10. bxc5 Nf6 ({But not} 10... Nxc4 $2 11. 
exd5 $1 {with a large advantage for White.}) 11. Bb3 O-O 12. g4 $1 {[%cal 
Gh1g1,Gh2h4,Gg4g5][%csl Rg8] White is underdeveloped, but the lack of defenders 
on the kingside allows White to strike with this move.} Nxg4 $2 {This is too 
risky. Black shouldn't be able to survive this.} (12... d5 13. Qe2 {and White 
keeps the Queens on the board and will attack in a similar way to the main 
variation.}) 13. Rg1 {[%cal Gg1g8][%csl Rg8]} Nxh2 14. Nxh2 Qh4+ 15. Kf1 Nxb3 
({If} 15... Qxh2 $4 {right away then} 16. Qg4 {and it is all over. The 
difference is that Black doesn't have ...g6 available because of the pin on the 
a2-g8 diagonal..}) 16. axb3 Qxh2 17. Qg4 {[%csl Rg8]} g6 18. Rg2 $1 {The only 
move to ensure a winning advantage. A key to understand is that we don't attack 
the King - we want to trap the Queen!} Qh1+ 19. Ke2 $18 {[%cal Gc1b2,Ga1h1][%csl 
Rh1] Bb2 comes next and the Black Queen is gone.} Kh8 (19... Kh7 20. fxg6+ $16) 
20. Bg5 {[%csl Rh1,Rh8]} Qxa1 21. Bf6+ Kg8 22. Qh5 {[%cal Gg2g6,Gh5h6][%csl Rg8] 
Only this move wins for White. It is a mate in four moves now.} *

