plans and go for a modest 3. g3 instead after both 2... Nc6 or 2... Nf6! Only 
after 2... Bc5 we will play 3. f4.}) Bc5 {In the first place, we will take a 
look at this continuation. It is the 3rd most popular move for Black and you 
should expect to meet it approximately once every 15 games. Black wants to 
develop quickly, and it makes more sense to continue with ...d6 since the 
dark-squared Bishop is already on c5.} 3. f4 $5 {This is the way to go for 
White. We are ready for a bare-knuckle fight. Other tries such as 3. Nf3 or 3. 
Bc4 are less critical. Also, after 3. f4 White scores a very respectable 60.8%.} 
d6 {This is the strongest move for Black. It allows our mighty opponent to keep 
the centre. The other tries should give White at least a slight edge.} 4. Nf3 
{Black's accurate 3... d6 forces us to enter the King's Gambit Declined 
positions. However, don't be too pessimistic about that! We've avoided a ton of 
2... exf4 lines and can confidently look to the future.} Nf6 (4... Nc6 5. Bc4 
Nf6 6. d3 {will lead to the same thing.}) 5. Bc4 Nc6 6. d3 {It looks like White 
may experience problems on the f2-square, but don't worry! If Black tries to put 
either of his minor pieces on g4 he will suffer.} O-O 7. f5 {The most promising 
and the highest-scoring move - 64% - that's a nice chess number! Black won't 
have a chance to develop the light-squared Bishop, and White's attack shouldn't 
be underestimated.} Nd4 {The 2nd most popular move. Black tries to exchange some 
pieces, but White will keep the initiative anyway.} 8. Nxd4 exd4 9. Nd5 Nxd5 10. 
Bxd5 {[%csl Gd5,Rc8]} c6 11. Bb3 {[%cal Ge1g1]} Qh4+ 12. g3 Qh3 {[%cal Re1g1]} 
13. Qf3 $1 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ge1c1][%csl Rc8,Ra8] White will finish developing with 
Bd2 and O-O-O followed by a kingside attack. Note how defenceless Black is with 
the c8-Bishop and the a8-Rook locked out of the game.} Re8 {[%cal 
Bc8f5,Bh3f5,Ge8e1][%csl Re1] Threatening to take on f5.} 14. Rf1 {[%csl Gf5,Rc8] 
Safeguarding the f5-pawn.} Bb4+ ({Of course not} 14... Qxh2 {due to} 15. Rh1 
{trapping the Queen.}) 15. Bd2 Bxd2+ 16. Kxd2 Qxh2+ 17. Rf2 Qh6+ 18. Qf4 $1 
{Even after the exchange of Queens White will maintain pressure.} Qxf4+ 19. gxf4 
$14 {[%cal Gf2g2,Ga1g1][%csl Gb3,Rc8,Rg7] White is a pawn down, but he can 
double the Rooks on the g-file. Also, White's Bishop is more active, so White 
enjoys at least a slight edge. This is the objective evaluation, but if we look 
at this position from a practical point I think it requires an engine-like 
performance to defend this position with Black.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The Vienna Game"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2...Nc6 3.g3 - White gets"]
[Black "a pair of Bishops - #8"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-vienna-game/course/28518, variation/4908719"]

1. e4 {We start with Fischer's favourite 1. e4! A move that allows White fast 
development and chances to fight for the centre.} e5 {Usually, 1... e5 is the 
biggest nut to crack for the 1. e4 player. Most of the 1. e4 aficionados are 
ready to face the Sicilian, the French and are happy with some sharp lines that 
may appear on the board. However, after 1... e5 things are far from clear. Times 
when White could destroy the opponent with romantic stuff such as the King's 
Gambit or the open Italian with d4 are gone due to the engines 'arrival'. 
Fortunately, there is a solution! We can still get a nice attacking position if 
we enter the Vienna Opening!} 2. Nc3 ({This is the aforementioned Vienna 
opening. Normally, Black will be perfectly ready for such tries as the Spanish, 
Italian, Scotch etc. However, it is more likely that Black's players won't be as 
booked to the teeth with modern theory against the Vienna as against the more 
popular lines. Even if they know theory in main lines with} 2. Nc3 2... Nc6 3. 
f4) ({or} 2. Nc3 2... Nf6 3. f4 {, they probably won't expect us to change our 
plans and go for a modest 3. g3 instead after both 2... Nc6 or 2... Nf6! Only 
after 2... Bc5 we will play 3. f4.}) Nc6 {The 2nd most popular move. Black just 
develops the Knight, but there is one important difference from the most popular 
2... Nf6. Black won't be able to play ...d5 quickly which is the most promising 
plan in the 2... Nf6 line. Here, the d5-square is not protected enough for this 
plan to work.} 3. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gg1e2] I started to play this line a few years 
ago, and I got some excellent results. With this move order, the pawn structure 
is more defined as Black can't play d5 very easily. This gives more freedom to 
prepare f4. This is a solid line which looks a bit like the Closed Sicilian for 
White, and Black can choose from many different setups.} Bc5 {Delaying ...Nf6 in 
favour of playing for a quick ...d6.} ({The mimicking try} 3... g6 {is also 
examined in the main course.}) (3... h5 $6 {is another try, the refutation of 
which is examined in the main course.}) 4. Bg2 d6 5. Na4 {[%csl Rc5] White has 
some plans to choose from, but I like the text move the most. We immediately go 
for the Bishop pair without letting Black play something like ...a6.} Bb6 {I 
think this doesn't pose White any serious challenge.} ({Alternative moves like} 
5... Be6) ({and} 5... Bd4 {are examined in the larger course.}) 6. Nxb6 axb6 7. 
Ne2 {[%cal Bd2d4,Bf2f4] White avoids ...Bg4 and can prepare both d4 and f4.} 
Nge7 8. d4 exd4 9. Nxd4 {This looks like a good version of the Scotch for 
White.} O-O 10. O-O {[%csl Gg2,Rc8]} f5 $6 {The only active plan for Black, but 
it opens up the diagonal for the White Bishop.} 11. Bg5 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 {[%csl 
Gg2,Gg5] Black has a very passive position.} h6 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. exf5 Rxf5 15. 
Rae1 $1 {[%cal Bg2b7][%csl Gg2,Rc8] Despite some exchanges, White keeps the 
initiative.} Re5 16. Bd5+ {Forcing the King to go into the corner.} Kh8 17. Rxe5 
Qxe5 18. Qxe5 dxe5 19. Re1 {[%csl Re5,Gd5,Rc8] Black loses a pawn.} c6 20. Bf7 
{[%cal Be1e5,Be1e7,Bf2f4,Bg1f2] White should try to bring the Rook on the 
seventh rank, then push f4 and bring the King into the centre.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The Vienna Game"]
