1. e4 {We start with Fischer's favourite 1. e4! A move that allows White fast 
development and chances to fight for the centre.} e5 {Usually, 1... e5 is the 
biggest nut to crack for the 1. e4 player. Most of the 1. e4 aficionados are 
ready to face the Sicilian, the French and are happy with some sharp lines that 
may appear on the board. However, after 1... e5 things are far from clear. Times 
when White could destroy the opponent with romantic stuff such as the King's 
Gambit or the open Italian with d4 are gone due to the engines 'arrival'. 
Fortunately, there is a solution! We can still get a nice attacking position if 
we enter the Vienna Opening!} 2. Nc3 ({This is the aforementioned Vienna 
opening. Normally, Black will be perfectly ready for such tries as the Spanish, 
Italian, Scotch etc. However, it is more likely that Black's players won't be as 
booked to the teeth with modern theory against the Vienna as against the more 
popular lines. Even if they know theory in main lines with} 2. Nc3 2... Nc6 3. 
f4) ({or} 2. Nc3 2... Nf6 3. f4 {, they probably won't expect us to change our 
plans and go for a modest 3. g3 instead after both 2... Nc6 or 2... Nf6! Only 
after 2... Bc5 we will play 3. f4.}) Nc6 {The 2nd most popular move. Black just 
develops the Knight, but there is one important difference from the most popular 
2... Nf6. Black won't be able to play ...d5 quickly which is the most promising 
plan in the 2... Nf6 line. Here, the d5-square is not protected enough for this 
plan to work.} 3. g3 {I started to play this line a few years ago, and I got 
some excellent results. With this move order, the pawn structure is more defined 
as Black can't play d5 very easily. This gives more freedom to prepare f4. This 
is a solid line which looks a bit like the Closed Sicilian for White, and Black 
can choose from many different setups.} Nf6 {This is one of the most natural 
developing moves for Black. He follows a classic principle - firstly, develop 
the Knights and only then think about developing the rest of your army.} 4. Bg2 
{[%cal Gg1e2] The most natural way of playing for White. The Knight will go to 
e2 and we will castle kingside.} Bc5 (4... d6 {would lead to similar positions, 
but with the Black Bishop shut behind the d6-pawn.}) 5. Nge2 d6 {This is the 
move that Black will play sooner or later, so it is best to start looking at it 
in the first line that features 2... Nc6. Both 5... Be6 and 5... O-O would 
likely transpose to 5... d6 followed by either 6... a6 or 6... Be6.} 6. O-O (6. 
Na4 {is an interesting alternative.}) h5 $5 {This is an aggressive approach that 
requires accuracy from White.} 7. h3 $1 {[%cal Rh5h4,Gg3g4]} (7. Na4 $2 {is the 
most popular move, but after} 7... h4 $1 {Black's attack is too strong to handle 
in practice. Do not allow that!}) h4 8. g4 {[%cal Bc3a4] This is the point of 7. 
h3. Now, if Black is determined to attack, he has to give up a piece.} Nxg4 9. 
hxg4 Bxg4 10. Kh2 $1 {[%cal Rh4h3,Rh3h2,Gg2h1] An important move to stop the 
h-pawn and to prepare f2-f3 in some cases.} h3 11. Bh1 Qh4 12. f3 {[%cal Rg4d1] 
White needs to break the pin.} Be6 {[%cal Bc5g1][%csl Rh2] Be very careful! 
Black threatens ...Bg1+!! with a mate in 5!} 13. d3 $1 {[%cal 
Rc5g1,Ge2g1,Rh4f4,Gc1f4]} ({White defends. Now, after} 13. d3 13... Bg1+ {White 
can just play} 14. Nxg1 {because the f4-square is defended by the c1-Bishop.}) 
O-O-O 14. Bd2 {[%cal Bc3a4,Bc3d5,Bd1e1,Be1g3][%csl Gh2] Black has some 
compensation, although White is a piece up. White should try to improve the 
Queen's position with Qe1-Qg3 and solidify the advantage by exchanging minor 
pieces with Na4. It is also an option to play Nd5 and Be3 while going for the 
pawn push f3-f4.} *

