1. e4 {We start with Fischer's favourite 1. e4! A move that allows White fast 
development and chances to fight for the centre.} e5 {Usually, 1... e5 is the 
biggest nut to crack for the 1. e4 player. Most of the 1. e4 aficionados are 
ready to face the Sicilian, the French and are happy with some sharp lines that 
may appear on the board. However, after 1... e5 things are far from clear. Times 
when White could destroy the opponent with romantic stuff such as the King's 
Gambit or the open Italian with d4 are gone due to the engines 'arrival'. 
Fortunately, there is a solution! We can still get a nice attacking position if 
we enter the Vienna Opening!} 2. Nc3 ({This is the aforementioned Vienna 
opening. Normally, Black will be perfectly ready for such tries as the Spanish, 
Italian, Scotch etc. However, it is more likely that Black's players won't be as 
booked to the teeth with modern theory against the Vienna as against the more 
popular lines. Even if they know theory in main lines with} 2. Nc3 2... Nc6 3. 
f4) ({or} 2. Nc3 2... Nf6 3. f4 {, they probably won't expect us to change our 
plans and go for a modest 3. g3 instead after both 2... Nc6 or 2... Nf6! Only 
after 2... Bc5 we will play 3. f4.}) Nf6 ({The most popular move for Black. 
Black is ready to play ...d5, but we have an additional tempo at our disposal. 
White's most popular reply is} Nf6 3. f4 {- 58.7% - but after} 3... d5 {Black 
has a good game. There is a lot of theory involved and it is not clear if White 
gets anything at all.}) ({The 2nd most popular choice is} Nf6 3. Bc4 {- 52.5% - 
and Black usually answers} 3... Nc6 {.}) ({There is also} Nf6 3. Nf3 {but it 
leads to the Four Knights Opening. The line that I want to offer is very similar 
to the previous chapter - 2... Nc6 3. g3. We will also fianchetto our 
light-squared Bishop in this chapter.}) 3. g3 {56.8% - This variation is very 
popular amongst top players from Azerbaijan, such as Mamedyarov, Mamedov or 
Safarli. White has similar ideas at his disposal as after 2... Nc6 - Bg2 + Nge2 
followed by O-O.} c6 {By playing this way Black tries to push ...d5 as fast as 
possible. If White continues in a normal way, then Black will fulfil the dream 
of expanding in the centre.} 4. d4 {We are not that cooperative though.} Bb4 $6 
{[%cal Bf6e4] This is the most popular move for Black, but it is very risky.} 5. 
dxe5 $1 {This is a punishment for Black's risky strategy. White should enter 
these complications without any fear.} Nxe4 6. Qg4 $1 {[%cal Bg4b4,Bg4g7] A rare 
move which seems to give White a big advantage.} Qa5 {It looks very dangerous 
for White, but complications favour our side!} 7. Qxg7 Bxc3+ $6 {This greedy 
move will be punished very hard.} 8. bxc3 Qxc3+ 9. Kd1 {[%csl Rh8]} Qd4+ 10. Bd3 
Nxf2+ 11. Ke2 {[%csl Ge2,Rh8]} Qg4+ {After all these checks Black managed to 
trade Queens, but the resulting endgame is a very tough one for him despite the 
extra pawn.} 12. Qxg4 Nxg4 13. Nf3 {[%cal Gh2h3][%csl Rg4] Black doesn't have 
anything developed and White threatens h3. Our advantage is overwhelming.} O-O 
{[%cal Rh2h3,Gg4e5,Bf3e5,Gf8e8]} 14. Re1 {[%cal Gh2h3] After 13... O-O, the 
following line wouldn't work for White:} (14. h3 $6 Nxe5 $1 15. Nxe5 Re8 
{winning back the Knight. White would retain the advantage anyway, but it is 
more critical to play as suggested.}) Re8 15. Kf1 {[%cal Gh2h3][%csl Rg4] Black 
needs to play d6 since White threatens h3. Then White takes the pawn, our 
Bishops are very active and the d-pawn is dangerous.} *

