complications favour our side!} 7. Qxg7 Rf8 {This will lead to beautiful lines.} 
8. Bh6 $1 {This is necessary to threaten Qxf8# so that Black's Bishop can't 
really abandon the a3-f8 diagonal.} Bxc3+ {It will be hard for Black to defend 
the Rook on f8 after this move, so Black is in trouble.} 9. bxc3 {[%csl Rf8]} 
Qxc3+ {[%cal Ge1d1,Re1e2]} 10. Kd1 $1 ({It looks very counter-intuitive to allow 
...Qxa1 with a check, but this is the way to go. If} 10. Ke2 $4 {then Black is 
better after} 10... Qxc2+ {, and something like} 11. Kf3 {leads to a disaster 
after} 11... Qxf2+ 12. Kxe4 $4 d5+ $1 {and Black wins!.}) Qxa1+ 11. Ke2 $16 
{[%cal Gg7f8][%csl Rf8] Black needs to play 11...d6 since White threatens Qxf8 
mate. Then White takes the pawn on d6 with the e-pawn, our Bishops are very 
active and the newly created d-pawn is dangerous.} *

