Gambit or the open Italian with d4 are gone due to the engines 'arrival'. 
Fortunately, there is a solution! We can still get a nice attacking position if 
we enter the Vienna Opening!} 2. Nc3 ({This is the aforementioned Vienna 
opening. Normally, Black will be perfectly ready for such tries as the Spanish, 
Italian, Scotch etc. However, it is more likely that Black's players won't be as 
booked to the teeth with modern theory against the Vienna as against the more 
popular lines. Even if they know theory in main lines with} 2. Nc3 2... Nc6 3. 
f4) ({or} 2. Nc3 2... Nf6 3. f4 {, they probably won't expect us to change our 
plans and go for a modest 3. g3 instead after both 2... Nc6 or 2... Nf6! Only 
after 2... Bc5 we will play 3. f4.}) Nf6 ({The most popular move for Black. 
Black is ready to play ...d5, but we have an additional tempo at our disposal. 
White's most popular reply is} Nf6 3. f4 {- 58.7% - but after} 3... d5 {Black 
has a good game. There is a lot of theory involved and it is not clear if White 
gets anything at all.}) ({The 2nd most popular choice is} Nf6 3. Bc4 {- 52.5% - 
and Black usually answers} 3... Nc6 {.}) ({There is also} Nf6 3. Nf3 {but it 
leads to the Four Knights Opening. The line that I want to offer is very similar 
to the previous chapter - 2... Nc6 3. g3. We will also fianchetto our 
light-squared Bishop in this chapter.}) 3. g3 {56.8% - This variation is very 
popular amongst top players from Azerbaijan, such as Mamedyarov, Mamedov or 
Safarli. White has similar ideas to the previous chapter at his disposal - Bg2 + 
Nge2 followed by O-O.} d5 {I think this is the most critical line. Black opens 
up the centre and it looks like a good version of the Scandinavian for him.} 4. 
exd5 Nxd5 5. Bg2 Nxc3 {This is by far the most popular move for Black. Our pawn 
structure is damaged, but capturing with the b-pawn strengthens our centre, and 
we can put pressure on the Black queenside using the newly-opened b-file.} 6. 
bxc3 {Black can choose between several setups based on where the dark-squared 
Bishop will be developed.} Nc6 {The most flexible move for Black which postpones 
the decision about the Bishop's development.} 7. Nf3 Bc5 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 Re8 
{This gives White a chance of expanding in the centre.} 10. d4 exd4 11. Rxe8+ 
Qxe8 12. cxd4 {[%csl Gd4,Gf3,Gg2,Rc8,Ra8]} Bb6 13. c4 {[%cal Gc4c5][%csl Rb6] 
White threatens c4-c5 and Black has to switch to 'tricks mode' to save this 
position.} Bg4 14. c5 Rd8 {The best resource for Black.} 15. cxb6 Nxd4 {[%cal 
Bd4f3,Bg4f3,Bd8d1] White will have to give up the Queen but we will enjoy 
tremendous compensation.} 16. Qxd4 $1 Rxd4 17. Nxd4 {[%csl Gc1,Gd4,Ga1,Re8,Ra7]} 
Qe1+ 18. Bf1 {[%csl Gc1,Ga1,Gd4,Be1]} axb6 19. Nb3 {[%cal Bc1e3] White needs to 
coordinate pieces. Nb3 is a good start because we defend the Rook and anticipate 
...Bh3.} c5 20. Be3 Qc3 21. Rb1 {[%cal Gb3d2,Bb1b8]} Bf5 22. Rd1 $14 {[%cal 
Gd1d8][%csl Gd1,Ge3,Gb3,Rc3,Rc5,Rb6] Finally, White manages to finish 
development and enjoys a slight edge. It is much easier to play with the pieces 
because White has only one weakness on a2.} *

